{"author":"RebarBotNava","data":{"fields":{"description":"Activity-based liveness for LLM gate ops using mechanisms compatible with the runner's synchronous `agent.run_sync()` architecture: a generous per-request read timeout + a per-tool timeout + step caps ‚Äî and NO total-runtime timeout. The stream-event idle-watchdog is explicitly DEFERRED (it needs an async runner).\n\n## Why\nA single hard total-runtime timeout truncates healthy multi-minute / large-context (1M-token) runs; liveness must be gauged by activity, not total elapsed time. BUT the runner uses `agent.run_sync()` exclusively (`src/rebar/llm/runner.py:323,461,474`) ‚Äî a blocking synchronous call that exposes no concurrent stream-event hooks. The LangGraph `idle_timeout` / Claude Agent SDK stall-watchdog pattern requires async `agent.run()` / `run_stream_events` and an event loop, which this synchronous runner does not have. So the correct, in-architecture design achieves activity-based liveness at request+tool granularity WITHOUT asyncio.\n\n## What\n- **Single-turn / structured calls:** a generous but finite per-request read timeout via `httpx.Timeout(read=...)` on the model's http client (sized above worst-case large-context prefill) + `request_limit=2`.\n- **Agentic calls (run_sync-compatible liveness):** the per-request read timeout (bounds a hung model call ‚Äî the real failure) + a **per-tool execution timeout** (`Agent(tool_timeout=...)`, bounds a hung tool) + **step caps** (`request_limit`, `tool_calls_limit`, optional `total_tokens_limit`, bounding infinite/oscillating loops). Between \"hung request\", \"hung tool\", and \"infinite loop\", a healthy long run is never truncated and a genuinely stalled/zombie run is always caught ‚Äî with no total-runtime timeout and no event loop.\n- **Deferred (ADR + follow-on ticket, NOT built here):** the sub-event stream-idle-watchdog (reset-on-stream-event) ‚Äî it requires migrating the agentic runner to async `agent.run()` / `run_stream_events`, which conflicts with the exclusive `run_sync` design. Capture the decision + the async-migration trigger in an ADR; file a discovered_from follow-on. If ever built, wrap the event iterator to avoid pydantic-ai #4796 (failing-tool + handler `AssertionError` masks the real error).\n- Tuning invariant: the `read` timeout must be >= worst-case single-request time-to-first-token (a 1M-token prefill can be minutes of silence) ‚Äî a too-tight read timeout is the truncation bug in miniature.\n\n## Scope\n- Per-execution_mode timeout wiring (per-request read + per-tool timeout + step caps); config keys with concrete defaults: `verify.llm_request_timeout_s` (default 600 ‚Äî generous enough for a large-context prefill), `verify.llm_tool_timeout_s` (default 120), `verify.llm_agentic_request_limit` (default 60), `verify.llm_agentic_tool_calls_limit` (default 200). Single-turn/structured uses the request timeout + `request_limit=2`. Values are starting defaults tunable per environment (CI/batch may raise them).\n- **Shared-client coordination:** the read timeout is set as an `httpx.Timeout` on the SAME `httpx.AsyncClient` that story 95a5 constructs (95a5 owns that construction seam) ‚Äî this story CONTRIBUTES the timeout into 95a5's client, it does not build a second client. Depends on 95a5's spike passing (transport injection viable) before this timeout wiring lands.\n- **Own timeout probe (distinct from the transport spike):** 95a5's spike proves `429->200` retry; it does NOT prove that an httpx read timeout (on the async client) and the per-tool timeout actually FIRE under `agent.run_sync()`'s internally-managed event loop. This story includes its own small probe: a `FunctionModel` that sleeps past the read timeout asserts the call is interrupted+classified under `run_sync`, and a sleeping tool asserts the per-tool timeout fires ‚Äî confirming the timeout mechanism is `run_sync`-compatible before the design is relied upon.\n- NOT in scope: any total-runtime cap (rejected ‚Äî truncates healthy runs); the async stream-event watchdog (deferred to ADR/follow-on).\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] A generous per-request read timeout is set for both modes (as `httpx.Timeout`), sized for large-context prefill, and configurable; verified by an injected slow-but-live model that returns just under the read timeout and is NOT aborted.\n- [ ] Agentic runs enforce a per-tool timeout + step caps (`request_limit`/`tool_calls_limit`); an injected hung tool trips the tool timeout, and a looping model trips the step cap ‚Äî each surfaces a classified failure.\n- [ ] A hung model request (no bytes past the read timeout) is aborted and classified; no total-runtime timeout exists anywhere in the gate path (asserted by test).\n- [ ] The whole timeout mechanism runs under `agent.run_sync()` with no asyncio introduced (verified ‚Äî no new event loop).\n- [ ] This story provides the content for the deferred-async-watchdog ADR (RECORDED by story 2eca, the sole ADR owner ‚Äî not authored independently here) and files the discovered_from follow-on ticket for the migration trigger.\n- [ ] `make test`/`make lint`/`make typecheck` green.\n\nFiles: `src/rebar/llm/runner.py`, `src/rebar/config.py`, `src/rebar/_config_schema.py`, `docs/adr/`.\n\n## Verified library behavior (experiment log ‚Äî pydantic-ai 1.107.0, httpx 0.28.1, offline)\nACTUAL captured output (no billable call):\n```\nAgent.__init__ has tool_timeout:            True   (per-tool execution timeout hook exists)\nAgent.run_sync has usage_limits:            True   (step caps go on run*, not the constructor)\nhttpx.Timeout(600.0, read=300.0, connect=10.0).read == 300.0   (per-request read timeout is settable)\nUsageLimits fields: [request_limit, tool_calls_limit, input_tokens_limit, output_tokens_limit,\n                     total_tokens_limit, count_tokens_before_request, ...]   (total_tokens_limit exists)\n```\nSo the run_sync-compatible liveness mechanisms this story wires ‚Äî httpx.Timeout(read=) on the shared\nclient (owned by story arcticduck), Agent(tool_timeout=), and UsageLimits step caps incl.\ntotal_tokens_limit on run_sync ‚Äî are all real 1.107.0 API. No asyncio / stream-event watchdog is\nintroduced (that path needs async agent.run(); DEFERRED per ADR). These are pydantic-ai/httpx LIBRARY\nsymbols, not rebar symbols (bug succinct-formable-kite: repo-absence != non-existence)."}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1783645040436179001,"uuid":"304aa46c-8bf8-43de-9716-f887d8e0cd04"}